WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.918
<i>[The Clarks'
"Better Off Without You"]</i>

2
00:00:02.919 --> 00:00:09.341
<i>♪ ♪</i>

3
00:00:09.342 --> 00:00:14.013
<i>- ♪ Oh-oh. oh-oh-oh ♪</i>

4
00:00:14.014 --> 00:00:16.015
<i>♪ You are sultry. dirty ♪</i>

5
00:00:16.016 --> 00:00:19.435
<i>♪ Soft. and hard ♪</i>

6
00:00:19.436 --> 00:00:23.147
<i>♪ You are close to me.
and you're so far ♪</i>

7
00:00:23.148 --> 00:00:25.899
[siren wailing]

8
00:00:25.900 --> 00:00:30.279
<i>♪ And I'm thinking of the time
we spent together ♪</i>

9
00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:34.616
<i>♪ Now I'll bury this
in my backyard ♪</i>

10
00:00:34.617 --> 00:00:37.119
[engine revving]

11
00:00:37.120 --> 00:00:42.332
<i>♪ Sometimes I sit and wonder ♪</i>

12
00:00:42.333 --> 00:00:46.837
<i>♪ If I'll never dial
your number ♪</i>

13
00:00:46.838 --> 00:00:52.259
<i>♪ 'Cause I'm having fun
looking out for number one ♪</i>

14
00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:58.098
<i>♪ And I'm doing all the things
I like to do ♪</i>

15
00:00:58.099 --> 00:01:03.270
<i>♪ I'm having fun
'cause I knew it all along ♪</i>

16
00:01:03.271 --> 00:01:07.649
<i>♪ I'd be better off
without you ♪</i>

17
00:01:07.650 --> 00:01:10.569
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18
00:01:10.570 --> 00:01:12.571
- Hey. I need my cast off.

19
00:01:12.572 --> 00:01:13.864
- As soon as you
park that outside.

20
00:01:13.865 --> 00:01:15.574
Morning. Doc.
- Olsen.

21
00:01:15.575 --> 00:01:16.992
Happy Fourth.

22
00:01:16.993 --> 00:01:18.660
{\an8}- Excuse me. guys.

23
00:01:18.661 --> 00:01:21.663
{\an8}- Sorry.
[person coughing]

24
00:01:21.664 --> 00:01:25.335
{\an8}[indistinct chatter]

25
00:01:37.514 --> 00:01:39.014
[device beeps. door clicks]

26
00:01:39.015 --> 00:01:42.060
[indistinct chatter continues]

27
00:01:46.231 --> 00:01:47.648
Hey. how's it going. Dad?

28
00:01:47.649 --> 00:01:49.483
- [sighs]
I'm so sleep-deprived.

29
00:01:49.484 --> 00:01:51.527
My house is starting to feel
like a CIA black site.

30
00:01:51.528 --> 00:01:53.487
- Have you considered hiring
a night nurse?

31
00:01:53.488 --> 00:01:55.239
- You're looking at him.
- You got a ripe one coming in

32
00:01:55.240 --> 00:01:56.907
you're gonna have to deal with
before everybody out there

33
00:01:56.908 --> 00:01:58.325
starts puking.
- Lovely.

34
00:01:58.326 --> 00:01:59.910
Your replacement came in early.

35
00:01:59.911 --> 00:02:01.703
She brought in a full
bagel spread.

36
00:02:01.704 --> 00:02:03.497
I'm just saying.
- She's not my replacement.

37
00:02:03.498 --> 00:02:05.040
She's just covering as chief
while I go

38
00:02:05.041 --> 00:02:06.416
on my little sabbatical.
- Three months?

39
00:02:06.417 --> 00:02:08.001
- I'll be back
before your daughter

40
00:02:08.002 --> 00:02:09.837
sleeps through the night.
- Hey. dude. that's cold.

41
00:02:09.838 --> 00:02:11.506
- Morning.
- Good morning.

42
00:02:12.924 --> 00:02:14.217
[elevator dings]

43
00:02:26.104 --> 00:02:27.729
- Good morning. John.
- [sighs]

44
00:02:27.730 --> 00:02:29.731
I could have sworn
it was still around 4:00 a.m...

45
00:02:29.732 --> 00:02:31.525
- Did you guys have
an easy night last night?

46
00:02:31.526 --> 00:02:33.193
The waiting room
actually looks manageable.

47
00:02:33.194 --> 00:02:35.112
- I wouldn't call it easy.
but not too bad.

48
00:02:35.113 --> 00:02:37.281
I figured we'd have hands
and burns down here a bunch.

49
00:02:37.282 --> 00:02:39.366
but so far nobody's
blown off any fingers.

50
00:02:39.367 --> 00:02:41.243
- Oh. you know
you just jinxed it.

51
00:02:41.244 --> 00:02:42.619
- [chuckles]
You guys and your jinxes.

52
00:02:42.620 --> 00:02:45.330
- Please. Jesus. please.
- Hail Mary again.

53
00:02:45.331 --> 00:02:47.332
- In the sanctified flesh.
- Don't let me die alone.

54
00:02:47.333 --> 00:02:50.586
- Just try to relax. Margaret.
- I need a priest.

55
00:02:50.587 --> 00:02:53.255
- Hey. hey. Dr. Robby.
- What's the good word. Perlah?

56
00:02:53.256 --> 00:02:55.174
- All your results came
back normal. Mrs. Walker.

57
00:02:55.175 --> 00:02:56.175
- I'm dying.

58
00:02:56.176 --> 00:02:57.593
- You're not dying.
Mrs. Walker. I promise.

59
00:02:57.594 --> 00:02:59.011
- Jesus is coming for me.

60
00:02:59.012 --> 00:03:01.305
- If He is. He hasn't checked
in at registration yet.

61
00:03:01.306 --> 00:03:02.639
- Please don't let me die
a sinner.

62
00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:04.224
- Don't worry. Margaret--
we're going to have

63
00:03:04.225 --> 00:03:06.226
the hospital chaplain come
and see you in a moment.

64
00:03:06.227 --> 00:03:07.728
- I'm not going
to last that long.

65
00:03:07.729 --> 00:03:09.563
- Yes. you will. because we're
going to give you a shot

66
00:03:09.564 --> 00:03:10.981
to keep you alive
until they get here.

67
00:03:10.982 --> 00:03:12.608
What are you thinking.
Dr. Robinavitch?

68
00:03:12.609 --> 00:03:14.484
500 mikes of cyanocobalamin?

69
00:03:14.485 --> 00:03:16.653
- In her condition.
I'd push a full 1.000.

70
00:03:16.654 --> 00:03:19.698
- Whoo.
You heard the man. Perlah.

71
00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:21.992
- God bless you.
God bless all of you.

72
00:03:21.993 --> 00:03:23.577
- Amen to that.

73
00:03:23.578 --> 00:03:25.579
- Hail Mary. full of grace.
the Lord is with thee...

74
00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:27.414
- Ooh. nothing like
the miracle healing powers

75
00:03:27.415 --> 00:03:28.916
of a good old B12 shot.

76
00:03:28.917 --> 00:03:32.085
How does she hold down a job?
- She doesn't.

77
00:03:32.086 --> 00:03:33.754
- She's wearing
a waitress uniform.

78
00:03:33.755 --> 00:03:35.297
- Yeah. from a diner
that closed 20 years ago.

79
00:03:35.298 --> 00:03:37.591
<i>- [over PA] Tier One Trauma.
ETA six minutes.</i>

80
00:03:37.592 --> 00:03:39.426
- And so it begins.

81
00:03:39.427 --> 00:03:41.929
- My husband is still waiting
to see a doctor.

82
00:03:41.930 --> 00:03:43.180
- I apologize for the wait.

83
00:03:43.181 --> 00:03:44.973
but here are two doctors
just for you.

84
00:03:44.974 --> 00:03:47.142
Mr. Burgess
has been complaining

85
00:03:47.143 --> 00:03:48.644
of leg cramps for a day.

86
00:03:48.645 --> 00:03:52.231
Slightly tachy at 110.
BP 128 over 75.

87
00:03:52.232 --> 00:03:54.191
Afebrile. good sats.

88
00:03:54.192 --> 00:03:56.151
- I'm Dr. Shen.
but I'm going off shift.

89
00:03:56.152 --> 00:03:58.403
Dr. Robinavitch will be one of
the doctors looking after you.

90
00:03:58.404 --> 00:03:59.696
- What other medications

91
00:03:59.697 --> 00:04:01.657
are you currently taking.
Mr. Burgess?

92
00:04:01.658 --> 00:04:03.784
- I brought his meds.

93
00:04:03.785 --> 00:04:05.786
- Thank you.
[dog whines]

94
00:04:05.787 --> 00:04:07.329
- These are his supplements.

95
00:04:07.330 --> 00:04:09.498
mostly all-natural and organic
where possible.

96
00:04:09.499 --> 00:04:12.292
And these are
his homeopathic prescriptions.

97
00:04:12.293 --> 00:04:16.338
I also have a list
of his refrigerated probiotics.

98
00:04:16.339 --> 00:04:19.049
[indistinct chatter]

99
00:04:19.050 --> 00:04:21.009
- Where the hell is everybody?

100
00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:23.262
- Our new attending
is torturing

101
00:04:23.263 --> 00:04:25.514
our intern and med students
in Trauma One.

102
00:04:25.515 --> 00:04:27.808
She came in early
to meet the night shift

103
00:04:27.809 --> 00:04:29.393
and took things over.

104
00:04:29.394 --> 00:04:32.312
- Okay. that takes giant balls
of disrespect.

105
00:04:32.313 --> 00:04:33.689
- Giant Balls of Disrespect

106
00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:35.482
was the name
of my band in high school.

107
00:04:35.483 --> 00:04:37.693
- [sighs] And my nickname
for my ex-husband.

108
00:04:37.694 --> 00:04:39.861
Hey. uh.
is this your last shift?

109
00:04:39.862 --> 00:04:43.824
- For a while. yeah.
- Oh. I am so jealous.

110
00:04:43.825 --> 00:04:46.493
Hey. I'll pay you a grand
if you take my second husband.

111
00:04:46.494 --> 00:04:47.744
- Tempting.

112
00:04:47.745 --> 00:04:49.705
So tell me about
this new attending.

113
00:04:49.706 --> 00:04:52.833
- Uh. she's pretty.
divorced. one kid.

114
00:04:52.834 --> 00:04:55.377
Can already tell
she is a strict rule follower.

115
00:04:55.378 --> 00:04:57.296
I'm probably going
to grow to hate her.

116
00:04:57.297 --> 00:05:01.049
- What's her name. again?
- Dr. Baran Al-Hashimi.

117
00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:03.719
- Al-Hashimi?
What is that?

118
00:05:03.720 --> 00:05:06.096
- Irish?
- [chuckles]

119
00:05:06.097 --> 00:05:09.057
- She's some sort
of clinical informatics expert.

120
00:05:09.058 --> 00:05:10.934
Once she started
talking about AI.

121
00:05:10.935 --> 00:05:14.354
I started thinking about robots
and kind of stopped listening.

122
00:05:14.355 --> 00:05:16.857
- Clear.
Off the chest. Ogilvie.

123
00:05:16.858 --> 00:05:18.400
Get ready to step up here. Joy.

124
00:05:18.401 --> 00:05:20.652
Ogilvie. off the chest!

125
00:05:20.653 --> 00:05:22.112
- Clear!
[alarm blaring]

126
00:05:22.113 --> 00:05:23.947
- Still V-tach.
but it looks weird.

127
00:05:23.948 --> 00:05:25.699
- Agreed.
- No pulse.

128
00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:27.826
- No effusion.
good lung sliding.

129
00:05:27.827 --> 00:05:28.869
- Start compressions. Joy.

130
00:05:28.870 --> 00:05:29.995
- We haven't considered
all the Ts.

131
00:05:29.996 --> 00:05:31.997
- I checked for tamponade
and tension pneumo.

132
00:05:31.998 --> 00:05:33.206
- What if it's thrombosis?

133
00:05:33.207 --> 00:05:35.417
If it's a pulmonary or cardiac
clot. TNK could save him.

134
00:05:35.418 --> 00:05:37.544
- We are sticking
with the algorithm for now.

135
00:05:37.545 --> 00:05:39.546
- Algorithm's not working.
- Faster and deeper. please.

136
00:05:39.547 --> 00:05:42.424
- Uh. you need a break. Joy?
- No. I need an attending.

137
00:05:42.425 --> 00:05:44.801
- I'm right here.

138
00:05:44.802 --> 00:05:46.720
Stop compressions.
We're calling it.

139
00:05:46.721 --> 00:05:48.221
[flatline]

140
00:05:48.222 --> 00:05:50.057
Sorry. the patient's dead.

141
00:05:50.058 --> 00:05:52.851
[flatline continues]

142
00:05:52.852 --> 00:05:55.395
All right.
Who can tell me what went well?

143
00:05:55.396 --> 00:05:57.105
- We followed
the V-tach algorithm.

144
00:05:57.106 --> 00:05:58.857
We checked
for reversible causes.

145
00:05:58.858 --> 00:06:00.609
- We limited our rhythm
and pulse checks to 10 seconds.

146
00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:01.985
- Excellent.

147
00:06:01.986 --> 00:06:03.278
- Should we have
given thrombolytics?

148
00:06:03.279 --> 00:06:04.654
- No. you should have
recognized

149
00:06:04.655 --> 00:06:06.782
that the cardiac rhythm
on the monitor was polymorphic.

150
00:06:06.783 --> 00:06:08.617
not just V-tach.

151
00:06:08.618 --> 00:06:10.577
It was <i>torsades de pointes.</i>

152
00:06:10.578 --> 00:06:12.788
That's French--
"twisting of the points."

153
00:06:12.789 --> 00:06:14.664
- From prolonged QT.
antiarrhythmics.

154
00:06:14.665 --> 00:06:15.999
electrolyte disorders.

155
00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:17.250
- Your patient would have lived

156
00:06:17.251 --> 00:06:18.960
if you had pushed
magnesium sulfate.

157
00:06:18.961 --> 00:06:20.837
- Good news is
he's an organ donor.

158
00:06:20.838 --> 00:06:22.589
Parts of him are going to get
used to make Frisbees

159
00:06:22.590 --> 00:06:24.800
and water bottles and end up
as microplastics

160
00:06:24.801 --> 00:06:26.510
in our brains
and reproductive organs.

161
00:06:26.511 --> 00:06:28.178
- Thank you for the words
of encouragement. boss.

162
00:06:28.179 --> 00:06:29.805
- Dr. Al-Hashimi.
Dr. Michael Robinavitch.

163
00:06:29.806 --> 00:06:31.765
Everybody calls me Robby.
- Baran. please.

164
00:06:31.766 --> 00:06:33.392
- Welcome to the Pitt.
- Yeah. about that--

165
00:06:33.393 --> 00:06:34.768
- Trauma's a minute out.

166
00:06:34.769 --> 00:06:36.728
- Ooh. who wants to treat
a real patient?

167
00:06:36.729 --> 00:06:38.146
- Yes. please.

168
00:06:38.147 --> 00:06:40.024
This thing's going
to give me nightmares.

169
00:06:41.776 --> 00:06:43.777
- I hope you don't mind me
jumping right into things.

170
00:06:43.778 --> 00:06:45.529
I find that a mock code
is a great way

171
00:06:45.530 --> 00:06:47.280
to assess
the students' capabilities.

172
00:06:47.281 --> 00:06:49.866
- Well. it might have been nice
if we'd had a little time

173
00:06:49.867 --> 00:06:51.618
to go over how we do things.

174
00:06:51.619 --> 00:06:54.621
- Did you not get a packet
from Dr. Underwood? Gloria?

175
00:06:54.622 --> 00:06:56.706
It outlined
the quality-improvement changes

176
00:06:56.707 --> 00:06:58.542
I instituted at the VA.

177
00:06:58.543 --> 00:06:59.835
We're adopting the program

178
00:06:59.836 --> 00:07:01.628
at all
of the university hospitals.

179
00:07:01.629 --> 00:07:04.005
You didn't read it?
- No. I did. I mean. I will.

180
00:07:04.006 --> 00:07:05.549
I'm going to.
I want to.

181
00:07:05.550 --> 00:07:07.217
I thought I had
a little bit more time

182
00:07:07.218 --> 00:07:09.177
before you came in today.
- We've already distributed

183
00:07:09.178 --> 00:07:11.680
patient passports
to everyone at registration.

184
00:07:11.681 --> 00:07:14.224
- What is a patient passport?

185
00:07:14.225 --> 00:07:16.810
- So glad you asked.

186
00:07:16.811 --> 00:07:18.645
Samira?
- Dr. Al.

187
00:07:18.646 --> 00:07:21.314
- We worked together
at the VA a few years ago.

188
00:07:21.315 --> 00:07:23.233
And now you're an R4.
- Yes.

189
00:07:23.234 --> 00:07:25.318
And I'm so excited
you're joining us.

190
00:07:25.319 --> 00:07:26.778
Dr. Mel King is here. too.

191
00:07:26.779 --> 00:07:28.196
I think you worked
with her as well.

192
00:07:28.197 --> 00:07:29.906
- Incoming!
- I did indeed.

193
00:07:29.907 --> 00:07:31.867
- John Doe--dishwasher.
penetrating trauma

194
00:07:31.868 --> 00:07:33.869
from a kitchen knife
to the right chest.

195
00:07:33.870 --> 00:07:35.328
- Assault or accident?
- Unclear.

196
00:07:35.329 --> 00:07:38.039
Initially had a pulse.
lost it two blocks away.

197
00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:40.417
[respirator hissing]

198
00:07:40.418 --> 00:07:42.502
- What do we got. party people?

199
00:07:42.503 --> 00:07:45.672
- Dr. Yolanda Garcia.
trauma surgery fellow.

200
00:07:45.673 --> 00:07:48.550
meet Dr. Baran Al-Hashimi.
new E.D. attending.

201
00:07:48.551 --> 00:07:50.427
She's gonna be covering for me
while I'm gone.

202
00:07:50.428 --> 00:07:52.012
- So nice to meet you.

203
00:07:52.013 --> 00:07:53.513
- About time they replaced you.
Rabbit-bitch.

204
00:07:53.514 --> 00:07:55.265
- I'm gonna miss you.
too. Yolo.

205
00:07:55.266 --> 00:07:57.601
Dr. Garcia has a hard time
expressing her feelings.

206
00:07:57.602 --> 00:07:58.643
- Not all of them.

207
00:07:58.644 --> 00:08:02.147
- One. two. three.

208
00:08:02.148 --> 00:08:05.484
Prep for a left thoracotomy.
- I'm on it.

209
00:08:05.485 --> 00:08:07.694
- What's up. White Chocolate?

210
00:08:07.695 --> 00:08:11.531
Did you know our farm boy here
is a vintage-funk freak?

211
00:08:11.532 --> 00:08:13.909
Unfortunately.
he also likes to use

212
00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:16.453
other people's toothbrushes.
- It was one time.

213
00:08:16.454 --> 00:08:18.079
They were the same color.

214
00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:20.081
- What's your plan. Samira?
- Dr. Mohan. next steps?

215
00:08:20.082 --> 00:08:21.416
- Chest tube to the right.

216
00:08:21.417 --> 00:08:23.210
Stand by with massive
transfusion protocol.

217
00:08:23.211 --> 00:08:24.461
- I put two units
on the infuser.

218
00:08:24.462 --> 00:08:25.795
- Sterile gloves. 6 1/2.

219
00:08:25.796 --> 00:08:26.880
- Here. we let the fellows

220
00:08:26.881 --> 00:08:28.298
and the residents
kind of take charge.

221
00:08:28.299 --> 00:08:30.467
- I'll hold on to them
just in case.

222
00:08:30.468 --> 00:08:33.470
- Is the VA even
a trauma center?

223
00:08:33.471 --> 00:08:37.057
- Not for medic runs.
but they walk in--

224
00:08:37.058 --> 00:08:41.102
falls. major MVCs. GSWs.

225
00:08:41.103 --> 00:08:42.604
- Stab wound's on the right.

226
00:08:42.605 --> 00:08:44.189
Why are we opening
the left chest?

227
00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:46.107
- Better access
if it's tamponade.

228
00:08:46.108 --> 00:08:48.026
and you can cross-clamp
the aorta.

229
00:08:48.027 --> 00:08:49.653
- Javadi. Whitaker.
sterile gloves.

230
00:08:49.654 --> 00:08:50.737
- Can I glove up?

231
00:08:50.738 --> 00:08:53.323
- It's best if you
watch the first one.

232
00:08:53.324 --> 00:08:55.034
- This guy's dead anyway.

233
00:08:56.994 --> 00:09:00.081
- 10 blade.
- 28 French on a long Kelly.

234
00:09:01.249 --> 00:09:02.791
- Javadi. you're on suction.

235
00:09:02.792 --> 00:09:05.752
Whitaker. get ready
for internal compressions.

236
00:09:05.753 --> 00:09:07.504
[cell phone chimes]

237
00:09:07.505 --> 00:09:09.423
- Sorry. that's my phone.

238
00:09:11.008 --> 00:09:12.592
- Finochietto retractor.

239
00:09:12.593 --> 00:09:13.927
Whitaker.
give me a little room.

240
00:09:13.928 --> 00:09:15.136
- I need to get to his heart.

241
00:09:15.137 --> 00:09:16.763
- I'm in.
Hook up the Thora-Seal.

242
00:09:16.764 --> 00:09:18.181
[cell phone chimes]

243
00:09:18.182 --> 00:09:19.474
- You want me
to get that for you?

244
00:09:19.475 --> 00:09:21.643
- Not right now.

245
00:09:21.644 --> 00:09:25.147
[hose slurping]

246
00:09:29.944 --> 00:09:32.029
- No tamponade.
pretty dry in here.

247
00:09:33.614 --> 00:09:35.198
Heart's empty.

248
00:09:35.199 --> 00:09:36.825
Somebody start cardiac massage.
I'll cross-clamp.

249
00:09:36.826 --> 00:09:37.993
- Yeah. I got it.

250
00:09:37.994 --> 00:09:39.411
You do these one-handed.

251
00:09:39.412 --> 00:09:41.454
pushing up against the
breastbone with four fingers.

252
00:09:41.455 --> 00:09:43.415
- Very good.
- Not much blood to suction.

253
00:09:43.416 --> 00:09:46.001
- Okay. team. I think we need--
- Samira. next steps?

254
00:09:46.002 --> 00:09:47.085
- Keep transfusing.

255
00:09:47.086 --> 00:09:48.587
Open the right chest.
- That is correct.

256
00:09:48.588 --> 00:09:50.380
Booties on. kids.
There will be blood.

257
00:09:50.381 --> 00:09:52.757
[indistinct chatter]

258
00:09:52.758 --> 00:09:54.635
- Frank?

259
00:09:56.137 --> 00:09:59.264
Langdon.

260
00:09:59.265 --> 00:10:01.474
Frank?

261
00:10:01.475 --> 00:10:04.019
- [exhales deeply]

262
00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:06.814
[indistinct chatter]

263
00:10:08.482 --> 00:10:10.650
- You should be good
to go now. hon.

264
00:10:10.651 --> 00:10:12.736
- Thanks. Lupe.
- Of course.

265
00:10:12.737 --> 00:10:14.614
Hey. go get 'em.

266
00:10:17.575 --> 00:10:19.993
- Hey. Doc.

267
00:10:19.994 --> 00:10:22.996
It's been a while.

268
00:10:22.997 --> 00:10:26.666
I got a-a bad toothache today.

269
00:10:26.667 --> 00:10:29.336
- We'll take care
of that. Louie.

270
00:10:29.337 --> 00:10:30.671
- All right.

271
00:10:35.426 --> 00:10:38.471
[device beeps. door clicks]

272
00:10:55.071 --> 00:10:57.072
- [clears throat]

273
00:10:57.073 --> 00:11:00.117
[chatter continues]

274
00:11:04.038 --> 00:11:06.247
- There's too much blood
to suction.

275
00:11:06.248 --> 00:11:08.249
Uh. retracting the lung.

276
00:11:08.250 --> 00:11:10.627
- Try to identify the source.
- Could be the right ventricle.

277
00:11:10.628 --> 00:11:12.587
- Or more likely. the hilum.

278
00:11:12.588 --> 00:11:14.381
- Fresh lap pads.

279
00:11:14.382 --> 00:11:15.632
[cell phone chimes]

280
00:11:15.633 --> 00:11:18.969
- Siri. turn on silent mode!

281
00:11:21.263 --> 00:11:25.476
[keypad beeping. locker buzzes]

282
00:11:42.284 --> 00:11:44.870
[keypad beeping]

283
00:11:47.707 --> 00:11:49.291
[locker buzzes]

284
00:12:03.514 --> 00:12:05.224
- [spits]

285
00:12:09.520 --> 00:12:11.104
- Good morning.

286
00:12:11.105 --> 00:12:12.856
- If it was a good morning.
I'd still be in bed.

287
00:12:12.857 --> 00:12:14.524
- [chuckles]
So what are you doing here?

288
00:12:14.525 --> 00:12:16.526
- Benji's mom is visiting
for the holiday.

289
00:12:16.527 --> 00:12:18.528
- She's still alive?
- That woman's too mean to die.

290
00:12:18.529 --> 00:12:20.155
Plus. who else is going
to get this place

291
00:12:20.156 --> 00:12:21.948
through
the Fourth of July weekend?

292
00:12:21.949 --> 00:12:23.783
- Sure as hell
ain't going to be me.

293
00:12:23.784 --> 00:12:26.119
- I rest my case.
What am I walking into?

294
00:12:26.120 --> 00:12:27.662
- Nothing too bad. yet.

295
00:12:27.663 --> 00:12:30.665
Uh. these are the ones
I'd keep an eye on.

296
00:12:30.666 --> 00:12:34.669
[gasps]
The prodigal son returns.

297
00:12:34.670 --> 00:12:35.837
Too soon?

298
00:12:35.838 --> 00:12:38.298
- No. I guess not.

299
00:12:38.299 --> 00:12:40.967
You're back.
- I took some time.

300
00:12:40.968 --> 00:12:44.179
I'm like an old trail horse--
I always find my way back home.

301
00:12:44.180 --> 00:12:45.930
You look good. kid.
How you feeling?

302
00:12:45.931 --> 00:12:47.891
- Uh. yeah. great.

303
00:12:47.892 --> 00:12:50.477
You know. it's been a...

304
00:12:50.478 --> 00:12:52.979
it's been a journey.
- I bet.

305
00:12:52.980 --> 00:12:54.647
- Thanks.
Robby around?

306
00:12:54.648 --> 00:12:56.566
- Uh. he's in with a trauma.

307
00:12:56.567 --> 00:12:58.985
But if you hurry back. you can
catch some of the pass-ons.

308
00:12:58.986 --> 00:13:01.238
They're in North.
- Uh. thanks.

309
00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:05.034
- I'll keep an eye on him.

310
00:13:07.161 --> 00:13:09.412
- I think we have
a lost little lamb.

311
00:13:09.413 --> 00:13:12.040
Uh. excuse me. hon.
Can we help you?

312
00:13:12.041 --> 00:13:14.000
- I'm looking
for the charge nurse.

313
00:13:14.001 --> 00:13:16.085
- Oh. well.
you found two of 'em.

314
00:13:16.086 --> 00:13:17.504
I'm Lena.
This is Dana.

315
00:13:17.505 --> 00:13:18.838
I'm night shift. going home.

316
00:13:18.839 --> 00:13:21.174
but Dana is queen
of the day shift.

317
00:13:21.175 --> 00:13:23.218
- Emma Nolan.
Nice to meet you both.

318
00:13:23.219 --> 00:13:25.678
Uh. I'm a new grad RN
here to shadow.

319
00:13:25.679 --> 00:13:27.222
- Welcome to the Pitt.
Emma Nolan.

320
00:13:27.223 --> 00:13:28.932
Here. let me put some
of your stuff behind the desk.

321
00:13:28.933 --> 00:13:31.726
and I'll give you a quick tour.
- Okay.

322
00:13:31.727 --> 00:13:34.229
- Where you from. sweetheart?
- Sault Ste. Marie.

323
00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:35.688
- Oh.

324
00:13:35.689 --> 00:13:38.233
- It's in Upper Michigan.
practically Canada.

325
00:13:38.234 --> 00:13:41.069
- My great-grandmother
was from up that way--

326
00:13:41.070 --> 00:13:44.239
nice area. a lot of bugs.

327
00:13:44.240 --> 00:13:46.074
How about a cup of coffee?

328
00:13:46.075 --> 00:13:47.450
[hose slurping]

329
00:13:47.451 --> 00:13:49.035
- Can't locate the source.

330
00:13:49.036 --> 00:13:50.829
- Proximal hilum
is under the sternum.

331
00:13:50.830 --> 00:13:52.831
- Along with most
of the right ventricle.

332
00:13:52.832 --> 00:13:55.625
- You need better exposure.
- Convert to a clamshell.

333
00:13:55.626 --> 00:13:58.044
- Exactly.
- Trauma shears.

334
00:13:58.045 --> 00:14:00.672
- Would've been nice to let
them come up with that plan.

335
00:14:00.673 --> 00:14:02.757
- Heart's going to need double
compressions just like this.

336
00:14:02.758 --> 00:14:04.133
[cell phone chimes]

337
00:14:04.134 --> 00:14:06.594
- Squeeze from the apex
to the aorta.

338
00:14:06.595 --> 00:14:08.137
[hissing]

339
00:14:08.138 --> 00:14:09.764
- Right ventricle looks good.

340
00:14:09.765 --> 00:14:11.224
- Massive hemorrhage
from the hilum.

341
00:14:11.225 --> 00:14:14.727
- Second MTP pack is going.
additional four units.

342
00:14:14.728 --> 00:14:17.146
- Hilar injury
looks very proximal--

343
00:14:17.147 --> 00:14:19.399
may be pulmonary artery
and vein.

344
00:14:19.400 --> 00:14:22.068
- Clamp's on.
Nope. no good.

345
00:14:22.069 --> 00:14:23.570
Still bleeding
like a stuck pig.

346
00:14:23.571 --> 00:14:24.571
- I can give it a try.

347
00:14:24.572 --> 00:14:25.947
- Dr. Garcia is
a very skilled surgeon.

348
00:14:25.948 --> 00:14:27.615
If she can't get it. we need
to think of something else.

349
00:14:27.616 --> 00:14:28.826
- Like what?

350
00:14:32.288 --> 00:14:33.788
- Hilar flip.

351
00:14:33.789 --> 00:14:35.456
We're going to rotate
the lung 180 degrees.

352
00:14:35.457 --> 00:14:37.083
like putting a kink
in the garden hose.

353
00:14:37.084 --> 00:14:39.836
It'll stop the bleeding.
- That could possibly work.

354
00:14:39.837 --> 00:14:43.590
- Or he'll die when you rip
the entire lung off the hilum.

355
00:14:43.591 --> 00:14:46.426
- Gently. very. very gently.
very. very slowly.

356
00:14:46.427 --> 00:14:49.471
[respirator hissing]

357
00:15:02.067 --> 00:15:03.902
- Blood loss is slowing down.
- That's a good sign.

358
00:15:03.903 --> 00:15:05.194
- Hilum looks dry.

359
00:15:05.195 --> 00:15:07.030
- Yeah. but the heart
feels empty.

360
00:15:07.031 --> 00:15:09.574
- Okay. we fixed the leak.
Now let's fill the tank.

361
00:15:09.575 --> 00:15:11.743
[cell phone chimes]

362
00:15:11.744 --> 00:15:13.828
You are very popular today.

363
00:15:13.829 --> 00:15:16.624
- Sorry. I'll turn it off
when I can.

364
00:15:20.794 --> 00:15:22.503
- Nine-year-old Kylie Connors--

365
00:15:22.504 --> 00:15:24.714
brought in by
her dad's girlfriend. Gina.

366
00:15:24.715 --> 00:15:27.133
Kylie took a tumble
on the stairs this morning.

367
00:15:27.134 --> 00:15:30.136
3-centimeter chin lac
and a chipped front incisor.

368
00:15:30.137 --> 00:15:32.055
She's got LET
on a pressure dressing.

369
00:15:32.056 --> 00:15:33.890
Bleeding pretty good
on arrival.

370
00:15:33.891 --> 00:15:36.059
Dermabond should do the trick.

371
00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:38.144
Any questions?

372
00:15:38.145 --> 00:15:40.521
Dr. King?

373
00:15:40.522 --> 00:15:41.981
Mel?

374
00:15:41.982 --> 00:15:44.568
- Oh. um.
I didn't say anything.

375
00:15:47.363 --> 00:15:50.156
- Uh. how you feeling. Kylie?
- Tired.

376
00:15:50.157 --> 00:15:52.951
- We've been here since 5:30.
- Oh. that makes two of us.

377
00:15:52.952 --> 00:15:55.328
But don't worry.
We'll patch you up good as new.

378
00:15:55.329 --> 00:15:57.956
And we will get you out of here
as soon as we can.

379
00:15:57.957 --> 00:15:59.374
Any questions?
- Can you raise your chin?

380
00:15:59.375 --> 00:16:01.250
- No. I'm just
her dad's girlfriend.

381
00:16:01.251 --> 00:16:03.294
so I'm new to all this.
- No worries. We got you.

382
00:16:03.295 --> 00:16:04.588
Next.

383
00:16:06.173 --> 00:16:10.051
- 26-year-old Liam Sanders--
took a fall from his bicycle.

384
00:16:10.052 --> 00:16:12.178
No LOC. nonfocal neuro.

385
00:16:12.179 --> 00:16:14.514
lower-leg lac
with no bony tenderness.

386
00:16:14.515 --> 00:16:16.349
- Were you wearing
a helmet. Liam?

387
00:16:16.350 --> 00:16:18.226
- No. I was just riding
in my neighborhood.

388
00:16:18.227 --> 00:16:20.019
- You should always
wear a helmet.

389
00:16:20.020 --> 00:16:21.521
- Hey. nice of you to join us.

390
00:16:21.522 --> 00:16:23.607
- Hey.
- Dr. Langdon!

391
00:16:26.026 --> 00:16:28.861
- Sold to Dr. Langdon.

392
00:16:28.862 --> 00:16:31.197
- Candace O'Grady. 82...
[person coughs]

393
00:16:31.198 --> 00:16:35.369
Brought in by her son Richard
for intractable vomiting.

394
00:16:37.204 --> 00:16:39.038
- Hardly any hemorrhage
on the right.

395
00:16:39.039 --> 00:16:40.456
- Looks like the flip worked.
- How's the heart. Whitaker?

396
00:16:40.457 --> 00:16:42.417
- Feels full of blood.
First time since we started.

397
00:16:42.418 --> 00:16:46.337
- Hold compressions.

398
00:16:46.338 --> 00:16:49.007
- Quivering bag of worms.
- Resume compressions.

399
00:16:49.008 --> 00:16:51.509
- When the heart quivers
like that. it's obvious V-fib.

400
00:16:51.510 --> 00:16:54.804
- Okay. internal paddles ready.
- Mm-hmm. Charge to...?

401
00:16:54.805 --> 00:16:56.597
- 25 joules.
- 50 joules.

402
00:16:56.598 --> 00:16:58.516
50 gets it right
the first time.

403
00:16:58.517 --> 00:17:00.685
[paddles whirring]
- Charged.

404
00:17:00.686 --> 00:17:01.978
- Okay. Whitaker.
when you're ready.

405
00:17:01.979 --> 00:17:04.023
- Clear.

406
00:17:06.608 --> 00:17:08.736
- That's what normal sinus
looks like.

407
00:17:10.529 --> 00:17:11.612
- Strong carotid.

408
00:17:11.613 --> 00:17:14.741
- Saline lap pads
and up to the OR.

409
00:17:14.742 --> 00:17:17.076
- That's a hell of a way
to start the day.

410
00:17:17.077 --> 00:17:20.913
- Unconventional.
but a decent outcome.

411
00:17:20.914 --> 00:17:23.249
- Why don't we split up
for efficiency?

412
00:17:23.250 --> 00:17:25.586
Residents present to either
one of us but not both.

413
00:17:27.087 --> 00:17:29.048
- We can certainly
discuss that.

414
00:17:33.510 --> 00:17:35.470
- Were you feeling weak
or dizzy?

415
00:17:35.471 --> 00:17:36.846
- [sighs]
No.

416
00:17:36.847 --> 00:17:38.598
I-I got up to pee.
and I tripped over

417
00:17:38.599 --> 00:17:40.600
a laundry basket that
I couldn't see in the dark.

418
00:17:40.601 --> 00:17:42.143
- Did you hit your head?

419
00:17:42.144 --> 00:17:44.103
- Does my chart say
that I hit my head?

420
00:17:44.104 --> 00:17:46.272
- No. we just
want to be thorough

421
00:17:46.273 --> 00:17:48.524
to make sure
you don't miss anything.

422
00:17:48.525 --> 00:17:50.860
- How about we focus
on patching me up?

423
00:17:50.861 --> 00:17:52.487
Ah!

424
00:17:52.488 --> 00:17:54.489
- All right. Mr. Williams.

425
00:17:54.490 --> 00:17:56.282
we're going to check an X-ray
of your wrist

426
00:17:56.283 --> 00:17:58.493
and try to get you out of here
as quickly as possible.

427
00:17:58.494 --> 00:18:00.995
- Great. And let's keep
the bullshit extra charges

428
00:18:00.996 --> 00:18:02.497
to a minimum. huh?

429
00:18:02.498 --> 00:18:04.791
My deductible
is already a bitch.

430
00:18:04.792 --> 00:18:07.293
- [sighs]

431
00:18:07.294 --> 00:18:09.129
Sure.

432
00:18:11.548 --> 00:18:14.593
[Samira speaking Tamil]

433
00:18:30.818 --> 00:18:32.235
Bye.

434
00:18:32.236 --> 00:18:34.695
My mother is trying
to destroy my life.

435
00:18:34.696 --> 00:18:36.864
- Yeah. they seem
to take pleasure in that.

436
00:18:36.865 --> 00:18:38.699
- I committed
to a partnership-track position

437
00:18:38.700 --> 00:18:40.535
next year at a hospital
back in Jersey

438
00:18:40.536 --> 00:18:42.537
so I could be close
and support her.

439
00:18:42.538 --> 00:18:45.540
But now she's getting married
and selling our house

440
00:18:45.541 --> 00:18:48.084
to go on a year-long cruise
around the world.

441
00:18:48.085 --> 00:18:50.670
- Wow.
I mean. that's a--

442
00:18:50.671 --> 00:18:52.630
- Pretty fucking stupid idea.
if you ask me.

443
00:18:52.631 --> 00:18:54.715
She's known this guy
less than a year.

444
00:18:54.716 --> 00:18:58.094
What if he's a player?
What if she disappears at sea?

445
00:18:58.095 --> 00:18:59.846
- I mean.
what if they're in love?

446
00:18:59.847 --> 00:19:01.514
- Lust is more like it.

447
00:19:01.515 --> 00:19:04.642
- That is even better.

448
00:19:04.643 --> 00:19:07.937
Man. it has been a while.

449
00:19:07.938 --> 00:19:11.357
and I'm solo this weekend.

450
00:19:11.358 --> 00:19:13.610
I need to get laid.

451
00:19:17.489 --> 00:19:19.615
It's a little much
before 8:00 a.m.. right?

452
00:19:19.616 --> 00:19:21.451
- [scoffs]
Yeah.

453
00:19:22.953 --> 00:19:24.746
Or ever.

454
00:19:30.210 --> 00:19:31.752
- How's it going. Esme?

455
00:19:31.753 --> 00:19:34.006
- Oh. just another day
in paradise.

456
00:19:47.769 --> 00:19:49.813
[device whirs]

457
00:19:51.231 --> 00:19:53.941
- Heard you're going on a trip.

458
00:19:53.942 --> 00:19:56.194
- Taking a sabbatical.
Leave tonight.

459
00:19:56.195 --> 00:19:58.029
- Where you going?

460
00:19:58.030 --> 00:20:01.866
- Um. Head-Smashed-In
Buffalo Jump.

461
00:20:01.867 --> 00:20:04.660
- Captain Crunch
flying squirrel socks.

462
00:20:04.661 --> 00:20:07.955
What. are we talking in code.
or are you having a stroke?

463
00:20:07.956 --> 00:20:11.417
- It's an Aboriginal UNESCO
Heritage Site in Alberta.

464
00:20:11.418 --> 00:20:13.419
I've never seen the Badlands.

465
00:20:13.420 --> 00:20:16.631
- What is this. like. uh.
some sort of spirit quest?

466
00:20:16.632 --> 00:20:19.926
- Uh. yeah.
something like that.

467
00:20:19.927 --> 00:20:22.553
- Look. I. uh--
I guess we should talk.

468
00:20:22.554 --> 00:20:24.931
Got a lot of things I need to--
- At some point. not right now.

469
00:20:24.932 --> 00:20:26.599
Right now
I got to hit the head.

470
00:20:26.600 --> 00:20:28.601
and I would like you to go
help Donnie out in Triage.

471
00:20:28.602 --> 00:20:29.936
- Triage?

472
00:20:29.937 --> 00:20:31.479
N-no.

473
00:20:31.480 --> 00:20:33.189
No. I already picked up
a patient in North 2.

474
00:20:33.190 --> 00:20:34.607
a bicycle fall leg lac.
so maybe--

475
00:20:34.608 --> 00:20:35.775
- Pretty sure
we can cover for you.

476
00:20:35.776 --> 00:20:39.028
We've been doing it for months.

477
00:20:39.029 --> 00:20:40.613
- Right.

478
00:20:40.614 --> 00:20:43.199
No. and I--and I am--
I am very. uh--

479
00:20:43.200 --> 00:20:44.951
both very sorry
and appreciative of that.

480
00:20:44.952 --> 00:20:46.452
I just would hate to think

481
00:20:46.453 --> 00:20:49.121
that this is some kind
of a punishment for...

482
00:20:49.122 --> 00:20:51.040
but. uh. yeah.
Yeah. No. for sure.

483
00:20:51.041 --> 00:20:54.669
We'll--we'll talk later.
before you go.

484
00:20:54.670 --> 00:20:57.129
- Like I said. not right now.

485
00:20:57.130 --> 00:20:59.507
Donnie just passed
his NP certification.

486
00:20:59.508 --> 00:21:01.426
He can help if you get in
over your head.

487
00:21:04.888 --> 00:21:06.847
Hey. Mel...

488
00:21:06.848 --> 00:21:09.725
can you take over
a bike fall leg lac in North 2

489
00:21:09.726 --> 00:21:11.602
for Langdon
while he's out in Triage?

490
00:21:11.603 --> 00:21:13.396
- Um. you know. I-I can work
in Triage if you want--

491
00:21:13.397 --> 00:21:15.273
- No. I want to keep Langdon
out in Triage.

492
00:21:15.274 --> 00:21:16.983
and I want to keep you
back here.

493
00:21:16.984 --> 00:21:19.485
You okay with that?
- Sure.

494
00:21:19.486 --> 00:21:21.488
- Great.
- Absolutely.

495
00:21:27.494 --> 00:21:29.203
- So...

496
00:21:29.204 --> 00:21:31.497
who should I pick up?

497
00:21:31.498 --> 00:21:33.499
- We're about to get
the morning rush.

498
00:21:33.500 --> 00:21:34.709
- What do you mean?

499
00:21:34.710 --> 00:21:36.210
- Every morning
around this time.

500
00:21:36.211 --> 00:21:38.671
the nursing homes
and assisted-living facilities

501
00:21:38.672 --> 00:21:41.341
do their morning bed checks.
- Uh-huh.

502
00:21:44.094 --> 00:21:46.638
It looks pretty quiet to me.

503
00:21:49.891 --> 00:21:52.101
- Huh.

504
00:21:52.102 --> 00:21:53.853
- Incoming.

505
00:21:53.854 --> 00:21:55.521
- Oh. like I said.

506
00:21:55.522 --> 00:21:57.064
Come on.

507
00:21:57.065 --> 00:21:58.607
- Ethan Bostick. 79--

508
00:21:58.608 --> 00:22:00.693
found altered this morning
at assisted living.

509
00:22:00.694 --> 00:22:02.028
No history of dementia.

510
00:22:02.029 --> 00:22:03.904
Has a POLST.
- What's a POLST?

511
00:22:03.905 --> 00:22:06.532
- Physician Orders
for Life-Sustaining Treatment--

512
00:22:06.533 --> 00:22:08.993
no CPR. no intubation.

513
00:22:08.994 --> 00:22:11.078
- Then there's--
there's nothing for us to do.

514
00:22:11.079 --> 00:22:12.913
- South 15 is open.

515
00:22:12.914 --> 00:22:15.916
Uh. well. "do not resuscitate"
does not mean "do not treat."

516
00:22:15.917 --> 00:22:19.754
He may perk up with fluids.
IV antibiotics.

517
00:22:19.755 --> 00:22:22.758
{\an8}- [speaking Korean]

518
00:22:24.551 --> 00:22:25.843
- What's the good word. Crash?

519
00:22:25.844 --> 00:22:28.220
You save
that ventriloquist dummy?

520
00:22:28.221 --> 00:22:29.930
- Yeah.
- Really?

521
00:22:29.931 --> 00:22:32.391
- No.
- [laughs]

522
00:22:32.392 --> 00:22:34.393
Wait. tell me
you're not actually charting

523
00:22:34.394 --> 00:22:36.562
about losing a mannequin.
- It's part of the exercise.

524
00:22:36.563 --> 00:22:38.397
Dr. Al-Hashimi
asked us to do it.

525
00:22:38.398 --> 00:22:40.399
- Who's his next of kin--
Barbie?

526
00:22:40.400 --> 00:22:41.942
[chuckles]

527
00:22:41.943 --> 00:22:45.946
What's your. uh. take
on the new attending?

528
00:22:45.947 --> 00:22:47.616
- Too soon to tell.

529
00:22:49.576 --> 00:22:50.910
You?
- [sighs]

530
00:22:50.911 --> 00:22:52.161
She's already bugging me

531
00:22:52.162 --> 00:22:53.788
about being behind
on my charting.

532
00:22:53.789 --> 00:22:55.456
Now I know why everyone says

533
00:22:55.457 --> 00:22:57.750
being a second-year resident
sucks--because it does.

534
00:22:57.751 --> 00:22:59.543
- I must've slept through
the part of med school

535
00:22:59.544 --> 00:23:02.380
where they tell you 90% of
your time will be spent typing.

536
00:23:02.381 --> 00:23:03.964
- Which is just one more reason

537
00:23:03.965 --> 00:23:06.175
surgery is
a better lifestyle choice.

538
00:23:06.176 --> 00:23:09.178
- Hey. Dr. Shamsi.
Dr. Trinity Santos.

539
00:23:09.179 --> 00:23:11.389
- Ah. yes. the ER intern
who's interested

540
00:23:11.390 --> 00:23:13.391
in my surgery program.
- That's me.

541
00:23:13.392 --> 00:23:15.976
But I'm an R2 now and thinking
of double boarding

542
00:23:15.977 --> 00:23:17.812
in surgery
and emergency medicine.

543
00:23:17.813 --> 00:23:20.314
which I know would sound
ridiculously ambitious

544
00:23:20.315 --> 00:23:22.650
if I didn't have the talent
to back it up.

545
00:23:22.651 --> 00:23:24.236
- And the required attitude.

546
00:23:25.862 --> 00:23:27.613
Are you here to see a patient?

547
00:23:27.614 --> 00:23:29.407
- I was. I did.

548
00:23:29.408 --> 00:23:30.783
And now I'm here to learn

549
00:23:30.784 --> 00:23:33.452
why you aren't returning
my calls or texts.

550
00:23:33.453 --> 00:23:34.995
- Okay. I'm out.

551
00:23:34.996 --> 00:23:37.123
Nice seeing you again.
Dr. Shamsi.

552
00:23:37.124 --> 00:23:38.666
- As soon as I get
a little free time.

553
00:23:38.667 --> 00:23:40.793
I will make plans for all of us
to do something together.

554
00:23:40.794 --> 00:23:42.628
- What about Tuesday?
- I'm working.

555
00:23:42.629 --> 00:23:44.505
- On your birthday?

556
00:23:44.506 --> 00:23:46.298
- I will call you
and Dad tomorrow.

557
00:23:46.299 --> 00:23:48.008
and we'll come up with something
to do together. I promise.

558
00:23:48.009 --> 00:23:50.010
But right now I actually have

559
00:23:50.011 --> 00:23:52.264
a bunch
of night-shift hand-offs.

560
00:23:54.641 --> 00:23:56.143
- [clears throat]

561
00:23:59.354 --> 00:24:03.107
- We have schedules.
You have chaos.

562
00:24:03.108 --> 00:24:05.234
You know she's wasting
her talents down here.

563
00:24:05.235 --> 00:24:08.237
- Victoria is a big girl.
She can make her own decisions.

564
00:24:08.238 --> 00:24:11.824
- She's also a young girl who's
still very impressionable.

565
00:24:11.825 --> 00:24:14.869
And you can be very...
- "Pressionable"?

566
00:24:14.870 --> 00:24:17.455
[cell phone ringing]

567
00:24:17.456 --> 00:24:18.831
- Yes?

568
00:24:18.832 --> 00:24:21.667
Who?

569
00:24:21.668 --> 00:24:24.462
Oh. for God's sake.
I'll be right there.

570
00:24:24.463 --> 00:24:26.964
We need to talk.

571
00:24:26.965 --> 00:24:29.301
- [whispering]
How about same time tomorrow?

572
00:24:31.887 --> 00:24:33.721
- Next Tuesday's your birthday?

573
00:24:33.722 --> 00:24:36.015
- No.

574
00:24:36.016 --> 00:24:38.267
Yes.
- Your 21st birthday?

575
00:24:38.268 --> 00:24:39.685
- Please don't
say anything. okay?

576
00:24:39.686 --> 00:24:41.061
I-I get a little anxious
about--

577
00:24:41.062 --> 00:24:42.563
- Dr. Santos. little girl
with the chin lac

578
00:24:42.564 --> 00:24:44.064
is getting into a gown.

579
00:24:44.065 --> 00:24:46.692
[whispering]
Don't want anyone to know what?

580
00:24:46.693 --> 00:24:49.028
- Nothing.

581
00:24:49.029 --> 00:24:50.946
- Have a good day.
- You too.

582
00:24:50.947 --> 00:24:52.615
{\an8}- [speaking Tagalog]

583
00:24:52.616 --> 00:24:53.950
{\an8}- [normal voice]
Oh.

584
00:24:55.368 --> 00:24:58.078
- Hey. Duke. I'm just calling
to remind you

585
00:24:58.079 --> 00:25:01.081
that this is my last shift
for a while.

586
00:25:01.082 --> 00:25:03.626
So I need you to come in
before 3:00

587
00:25:03.627 --> 00:25:07.087
in case we need
to run some tests.

588
00:25:07.088 --> 00:25:09.758
Okay?
We had a deal. brother.

589
00:25:11.801 --> 00:25:13.928
Oh. Hello.
- Hi.

590
00:25:13.929 --> 00:25:16.096
I know you're crazy busy.
- Always.

591
00:25:16.097 --> 00:25:18.182
- But I figured we should
really go over a few things

592
00:25:18.183 --> 00:25:19.725
before you're gone.
- Sure.

593
00:25:19.726 --> 00:25:21.810
Where would you like to start?

594
00:25:21.811 --> 00:25:23.521
- Well. one little thing
that I think

595
00:25:23.522 --> 00:25:26.106
would have a big impact
with staff and patients alike

596
00:25:26.107 --> 00:25:27.942
is if we launched a campaign

597
00:25:27.943 --> 00:25:31.111
to eradicate referring
to this wonderful department

598
00:25:31.112 --> 00:25:33.739
as the Pitt.
- Really?

599
00:25:33.740 --> 00:25:35.741
- I know you think
it's silly and petty.

600
00:25:35.742 --> 00:25:37.743
- No. I think it's
just kind of endearing.

601
00:25:37.744 --> 00:25:41.622
pretty damn accurate.
- I would argue the opposite.

602
00:25:41.623 --> 00:25:44.124
I think subconsciously
it affects those who work here.

603
00:25:44.125 --> 00:25:45.751
It also lowers expectations.

604
00:25:45.752 --> 00:25:48.128
which in turn lowers
patient-satisfaction scores.

605
00:25:48.129 --> 00:25:49.964
- You have been talking
to Gloria.

606
00:25:49.965 --> 00:25:53.425
- Yes. and she agrees with me.
- Don't doubt that for a moment.

607
00:25:53.426 --> 00:25:55.261
- You have to see the man
over there right now!

608
00:25:55.262 --> 00:25:57.846
- We see people in order
of severity. ma'am.

609
00:25:57.847 --> 00:26:01.267
- [speaking Ukrainian]

610
00:26:01.268 --> 00:26:02.768
- I don't know
what you're saying.

611
00:26:02.769 --> 00:26:05.104
- I can taste the shit
in the back of my throat.

612
00:26:05.105 --> 00:26:06.355
- Actually. the lady's right.

613
00:26:06.356 --> 00:26:07.982
He's going to make
all of us sick.

614
00:26:07.983 --> 00:26:09.066
- Yes. please.

615
00:26:09.067 --> 00:26:11.194
[indistinct chatter]

616
00:26:13.822 --> 00:26:15.864
- [coughing]

617
00:26:15.865 --> 00:26:17.449
- All right.
[sighs]

618
00:26:17.450 --> 00:26:18.993
We'll get him back.

619
00:26:18.994 --> 00:26:21.412
Tell Dana
we're bringing the funk.

620
00:26:21.413 --> 00:26:23.456
- Oh. my God.
- Whew!

621
00:26:24.291 --> 00:26:26.792
- So when did your eye start
bothering you. Ms. Mathews?

622
00:26:26.793 --> 00:26:28.836
- Sister Grace. please.

623
00:26:28.837 --> 00:26:30.879
I'm only married to God.

624
00:26:30.880 --> 00:26:32.590
- Of course. I'm sorry.

625
00:26:32.591 --> 00:26:36.176
- A few days ago.
I thought it was pink eye

626
00:26:36.177 --> 00:26:38.387
or maybe I scratched it
while gardening.

627
00:26:38.388 --> 00:26:40.639
- It's a very bad case
of conjunctivitis.

628
00:26:40.640 --> 00:26:42.391
We should send a sample
to the lab

629
00:26:42.392 --> 00:26:43.851
to direct our treatment.

630
00:26:43.852 --> 00:26:45.729
Look up for me.
Thank you.

631
00:26:48.982 --> 00:26:51.817
Okay. I'll put a numbing drop
in your eye

632
00:26:51.818 --> 00:26:54.863
and check for a scratch
with a special lamp.

633
00:26:57.824 --> 00:26:59.825
And I'll get you
to look up for me again.

634
00:26:59.826 --> 00:27:01.660
Thank you.

635
00:27:01.661 --> 00:27:04.163
- Have you ever considered
serving God?

636
00:27:04.164 --> 00:27:05.331
- Which one?

637
00:27:05.332 --> 00:27:07.666
- Excuse me?

638
00:27:07.667 --> 00:27:09.418
- My family is Hindu.

639
00:27:09.419 --> 00:27:12.212
so we have. like.
33 different kinds of deities.

640
00:27:12.213 --> 00:27:14.465
- Oh. we have the one.

641
00:27:14.466 --> 00:27:17.509
- Some people
only need one. right?

642
00:27:17.510 --> 00:27:19.011
Okay.

643
00:27:19.012 --> 00:27:21.138
[camera shutter clicks]

644
00:27:21.139 --> 00:27:24.016
- Most important rule
around here--be smart. be safe.

645
00:27:24.017 --> 00:27:26.060
I can't warn you enough
about protecting yourself

646
00:27:26.061 --> 00:27:27.478
and your fellow nurses.

647
00:27:27.479 --> 00:27:29.938
We use the STAMP acronym
to assess patients.

648
00:27:29.939 --> 00:27:31.357
You know it?

649
00:27:31.358 --> 00:27:33.901
- Uh. S is for staring
or refusal to make eye contact.

650
00:27:33.902 --> 00:27:35.569
- If they're staring.
they're scaring.

651
00:27:35.570 --> 00:27:37.112
T?
- Tone of voice.

652
00:27:37.113 --> 00:27:39.490
- Often the threat level
rises with their voice.

653
00:27:39.491 --> 00:27:40.949
- A is for anxiety.

654
00:27:40.950 --> 00:27:42.618
- You can also think
"aggression."

655
00:27:42.619 --> 00:27:44.036
- M is mumbling.

656
00:27:44.037 --> 00:27:45.245
- Which. if you
listen closely enough.

657
00:27:45.246 --> 00:27:46.914
is often them saying
what they're thinking of doing

658
00:27:46.915 --> 00:27:48.582
as they talk themselves
up to it.

659
00:27:48.583 --> 00:27:50.125
And P?
- Pacing.

660
00:27:50.126 --> 00:27:51.543
- Good.

661
00:27:51.544 --> 00:27:53.462
We also have a safe word--
"hula hoop."

662
00:27:53.463 --> 00:27:55.255
I guess technically
it's two words. but whatever.

663
00:27:55.256 --> 00:27:57.257
If there's a threat.
say "hula hoop."

664
00:27:57.258 --> 00:28:00.719
and we'll all respond.
[cell phone ringing]

665
00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:02.262
Yeah?

666
00:28:02.263 --> 00:28:03.722
Lovely.

667
00:28:03.723 --> 00:28:07.893
Okay. I'll be right there
with reinforcements.

668
00:28:07.894 --> 00:28:10.730
Duty calls.
We're headed for Triage.

669
00:28:13.858 --> 00:28:16.485
[indistinct chatter]

670
00:28:16.486 --> 00:28:18.445
- We're going to get
your cast off--

671
00:28:18.446 --> 00:28:21.491
[low humming]

672
00:28:37.507 --> 00:28:40.217
- The antibiotics
should clear everything up.

673
00:28:40.218 --> 00:28:43.137
but you should try to stay
off it for a few days.

674
00:28:43.138 --> 00:28:46.515
- Uh. I have to work.
I'm late as it is.

675
00:28:46.516 --> 00:28:50.519
- Well. um. take breaks
and elevate when you can.

676
00:28:50.520 --> 00:28:52.354
Tylenol and Advil for the pain.

677
00:28:52.355 --> 00:28:55.107
If the pain persists or feel
like it's getting worse.

678
00:28:55.108 --> 00:28:56.316
come on back.

679
00:28:56.317 --> 00:28:58.652
We'll get you fixed up.
- Thanks.

680
00:28:58.653 --> 00:29:01.697
- They said give this
to the doctor.

681
00:29:01.698 --> 00:29:04.783
- What the hell is it?
- Patient passport.

682
00:29:04.784 --> 00:29:06.785
Lets patients know
what they're waiting for

683
00:29:06.786 --> 00:29:08.287
and how long it'll take.

684
00:29:08.288 --> 00:29:10.539
You check off if he needs labs.
X-rays. CT.

685
00:29:10.540 --> 00:29:12.499
- None of the above.
When did we start this?

686
00:29:12.500 --> 00:29:14.543
- Today. the new attending.

687
00:29:14.544 --> 00:29:16.295
- [scoffs]

688
00:29:16.296 --> 00:29:18.630
What's up
with your tooth. Louie?

689
00:29:18.631 --> 00:29:21.341
- It's been going on
for a while.

690
00:29:21.342 --> 00:29:23.343
but it got bad last night.

691
00:29:23.344 --> 00:29:25.971
[groans]
Lower-left side.

692
00:29:25.972 --> 00:29:28.140
- Okay.

693
00:29:28.141 --> 00:29:31.602
- [groaning in pain]
- Oh. yeah.

694
00:29:31.603 --> 00:29:33.479
It could be an infection
at the root.

695
00:29:33.480 --> 00:29:36.648
- [groans]
- We can drain it. but then...

696
00:29:36.649 --> 00:29:38.817
you're. uh--you're breathing
kind of fast.

697
00:29:38.818 --> 00:29:40.736
- [exhales sharply]
Yeah. I've been--

698
00:29:40.737 --> 00:29:44.198
well. I've been.
uh. walking more.

699
00:29:44.199 --> 00:29:45.866
trying to get in shape.

700
00:29:45.867 --> 00:29:48.702
But sometimes I get
a little short of breath.

701
00:29:48.703 --> 00:29:51.747
- Yeah. you need to walk past
the liquor store. not into it.

702
00:29:51.748 --> 00:29:54.374
Only shape you're getting in
is for a liver transplant.

703
00:29:54.375 --> 00:29:57.377
- I don't need a new liver.
Just get rid of this toothache.

704
00:29:57.378 --> 00:29:58.837
- Deep breath.

705
00:29:58.838 --> 00:30:02.591
- [breathes deeply]

706
00:30:02.592 --> 00:30:04.218
- One more.

707
00:30:04.219 --> 00:30:06.845
- Is my heart still ticking?
- Like a jackrabbit.

708
00:30:06.846 --> 00:30:10.057
How long you been sitting down?
- Oh. just for a few minutes.

709
00:30:10.058 --> 00:30:11.600
Not that long.

710
00:30:11.601 --> 00:30:13.436
- Um. Louie...

711
00:30:15.230 --> 00:30:17.440
There's something
I need to tell you.

712
00:30:19.776 --> 00:30:23.028
Last time I saw you.
about ten months ago.

713
00:30:23.029 --> 00:30:27.825
I treated you. and I took
some of your medicine.

714
00:30:27.826 --> 00:30:30.911
- I'm not sure I follow.

715
00:30:30.912 --> 00:30:33.580
- I have an addiction
to benzos.

716
00:30:33.581 --> 00:30:37.251
and I helped myself to some
of the Librium I prescribed you

717
00:30:37.252 --> 00:30:38.877
for your withdrawal.

718
00:30:38.878 --> 00:30:40.797
- You stole my pills?

719
00:30:42.507 --> 00:30:44.007
- Yeah.

720
00:30:44.008 --> 00:30:46.510
Yes. um...

721
00:30:46.511 --> 00:30:49.137
I'm sorry.
It was. uh...

722
00:30:49.138 --> 00:30:52.057
it was not only wrong
and utterly unprofessional.

723
00:30:52.058 --> 00:30:54.810
but it was a betrayal
of my Hippocratic Oath.

724
00:30:54.811 --> 00:30:58.063
and it was a fucking crime.

725
00:30:58.064 --> 00:31:02.485
That's where I've been--
rehab and counseling.

726
00:31:04.279 --> 00:31:06.905
- Huh.
- I'm sorry.

727
00:31:06.906 --> 00:31:09.783
I-I understand if you'd prefer
a different doctor.

728
00:31:09.784 --> 00:31:13.245
- Hey. Doc.
we have a situation.

729
00:31:13.246 --> 00:31:15.664
- Excuse me.

730
00:31:15.665 --> 00:31:17.082
What kind of situation?

731
00:31:17.083 --> 00:31:19.668
- Someone left a little baby
in the restroom.

732
00:31:19.669 --> 00:31:22.005
[baby crying]

733
00:31:27.844 --> 00:31:29.761
- Okay. let's think

734
00:31:29.762 --> 00:31:32.681
about reversible causes
of confusion in the elderly.

735
00:31:32.682 --> 00:31:36.310
- Uh. hypo or hypernatremia.
infection. but he's afebrile.

736
00:31:36.311 --> 00:31:38.228
good O2 sats.
and urine dip is negative.

737
00:31:38.229 --> 00:31:42.316
- Yeah. great.
Joy. anything to add?

738
00:31:42.317 --> 00:31:44.902
- Nah.
[alarm blaring]

739
00:31:44.903 --> 00:31:47.363
- V-tach. Can I--
- Yeah.

740
00:31:49.115 --> 00:31:51.033
- No pulse.
Should we call for a code blue?

741
00:31:51.034 --> 00:31:55.037
- No CPR. no shock. we honor
his POLST and his wishes.

742
00:31:55.038 --> 00:31:58.624
- So what does that leave us?

743
00:31:58.625 --> 00:32:01.293
- Making sure he's comfortable.

744
00:32:01.294 --> 00:32:02.794
- I'll suction.

745
00:32:02.795 --> 00:32:05.005
- Altered mental
in the elderly can also be

746
00:32:05.006 --> 00:32:09.427
toxicity from anticholinergics.
sedative-hypnotics. opioids.

747
00:32:10.887 --> 00:32:13.138
A-am I missing something?

748
00:32:13.139 --> 00:32:15.223
- Social skills?

749
00:32:15.224 --> 00:32:17.517
- [chuckles]
- What?

750
00:32:17.518 --> 00:32:20.062
[blaring continues]

751
00:32:20.063 --> 00:32:21.396
- He looks so peaceful.

752
00:32:21.397 --> 00:32:22.606
- Shouldn't we go find
a new patient?

753
00:32:22.607 --> 00:32:25.233
- No. stay here.

754
00:32:25.234 --> 00:32:27.027
[flatline]

755
00:32:27.028 --> 00:32:29.072
- Asystole.

756
00:32:37.997 --> 00:32:40.290
- Quick and painless.

757
00:32:40.291 --> 00:32:42.084
We should all be so lucky.

758
00:32:42.085 --> 00:32:44.169
- I'll try to contact
some family.

759
00:32:44.170 --> 00:32:45.754
[flatline stops]

760
00:32:45.755 --> 00:32:49.217
- Yeah. one of the things
we like to do here...

761
00:32:52.095 --> 00:32:54.179
When we have the time...

762
00:32:54.180 --> 00:32:57.015
is to take a moment of silence
when we lose a patient

763
00:32:57.016 --> 00:32:59.393
to respect their humanity.

764
00:32:59.394 --> 00:33:03.522
He was someone's son.
perhaps a father himself.

765
00:33:03.523 --> 00:33:06.025
a brother or a friend.

766
00:33:08.778 --> 00:33:12.198
Oh. uh. make sure
your phones are on silent.

767
00:33:16.369 --> 00:33:19.037
Great. great. great.
Okay. Uh...

768
00:33:19.038 --> 00:33:22.416
- Is anyone missing a baby?

769
00:33:22.417 --> 00:33:26.753
Did anyone leave their child
in the restroom?

770
00:33:26.754 --> 00:33:30.257
- Do you. uh. remember seeing
a woman enter with a baby

771
00:33:30.258 --> 00:33:32.134
but leave without one?

772
00:33:32.135 --> 00:33:34.428
- No. sorry.

773
00:33:34.429 --> 00:33:36.430
Might be on the security tapes.

774
00:33:36.431 --> 00:33:38.682
I'll have Ahmad check it out.
- Please.

775
00:33:38.683 --> 00:33:39.850
- Yeah.

776
00:33:39.851 --> 00:33:42.185
<i>- Harlow Graham to window one.</i>

777
00:33:42.186 --> 00:33:45.522
<i>Harlow Graham to window one.</i>

778
00:33:45.523 --> 00:33:49.485
<i>Harlow Graham to window one.
please.</i>

779
00:33:54.282 --> 00:33:56.074
- Donnie Donahue.
nurse practitioner.

780
00:33:56.075 --> 00:33:57.451
This is Emma. new grad nurse.

781
00:33:57.452 --> 00:33:58.994
- Hey.
- Nice to meet you.

782
00:33:58.995 --> 00:34:00.829
- What's going on?
- Somebody dumped their kid.

783
00:34:00.830 --> 00:34:03.457
- Maybe Mom just stepped out
for a smoke or something.

784
00:34:03.458 --> 00:34:05.250
What?
I'm being helpful.

785
00:34:05.251 --> 00:34:06.793
Sometimes they just need
a little break.

786
00:34:06.794 --> 00:34:09.254
and then they come back.

787
00:34:09.255 --> 00:34:10.922
At least they didn't leave her
in a suitcase

788
00:34:10.923 --> 00:34:13.258
at the bus station.
- Does that happen?

789
00:34:13.259 --> 00:34:15.135
- If that's a true story.
I don't want to know about it.

790
00:34:15.136 --> 00:34:17.262
- It ain't the worst I've seen.
- Please. don't tell me.

791
00:34:17.263 --> 00:34:19.682
I'm a new dad. remember?
- Okay.

792
00:34:22.018 --> 00:34:25.063
[baby crying]

793
00:34:26.647 --> 00:34:28.648
There you go.
I'll get Robby.

794
00:34:28.649 --> 00:34:30.358
- Should I come with?
- No. stay here.

795
00:34:30.359 --> 00:34:32.653
Donnie. Jesse.
teach her something.

796
00:34:35.364 --> 00:34:39.117
- You know how to check
a rectal temp on an infant?

797
00:34:39.118 --> 00:34:40.744
- Uh...

798
00:34:40.745 --> 00:34:42.663
theoretically.

799
00:34:48.169 --> 00:34:51.046
- Mr. Williams. how's the pain?

800
00:34:51.047 --> 00:34:52.672
- Nothing I can't manage

801
00:34:52.673 --> 00:34:54.674
with some Vicodin
and a little scotch.

802
00:34:54.675 --> 00:34:57.302
- [chuckles] Well. it's best
not to mix the two.

803
00:34:57.303 --> 00:34:59.638
James here is going to take you
to get an X-ray of your wrist.

804
00:34:59.639 --> 00:35:01.515
- I'm going to be fine.

805
00:35:01.516 --> 00:35:03.975
- Well. it'll tell us
if you need a cast.

806
00:35:03.976 --> 00:35:05.644
- Oh. I doubt it.

807
00:35:05.645 --> 00:35:07.896
I should probably go home.
keep some ice on it.

808
00:35:07.897 --> 00:35:10.690
I know you guys
always need the beds.

809
00:35:10.691 --> 00:35:13.068
- Well. uh.
it'll only take a minute.

810
00:35:13.069 --> 00:35:14.820
and then we'll know for sure.

811
00:35:14.821 --> 00:35:16.905
- Yeah. I-I really don't think
it's necessary.

812
00:35:16.906 --> 00:35:19.450
And I have a busy day.
but I appreciate your concern.

813
00:35:22.703 --> 00:35:25.247
- I'd really like to observe you
for a little bit.

814
00:35:25.248 --> 00:35:27.833
in case you did hit your head.

815
00:35:27.834 --> 00:35:29.417
- My head?

816
00:35:29.418 --> 00:35:31.878
I hit my schnoz on my arm.
I think. nothing more.

817
00:35:31.879 --> 00:35:34.172
- You think?
You don't remember?

818
00:35:34.173 --> 00:35:35.632
- No.

819
00:35:35.633 --> 00:35:37.467
Or. yes.

820
00:35:37.468 --> 00:35:40.512
I'm going to be fine. really.

821
00:35:40.513 --> 00:35:42.765
But thank you for your concern.

822
00:35:46.477 --> 00:35:48.270
- Okay.

823
00:35:48.271 --> 00:35:50.564
- [shouts in pain]

824
00:35:50.565 --> 00:35:54.234
- How about we take that X-ray
just to be safe?

825
00:35:54.235 --> 00:35:56.736
- Yeah. Yeah. okay.
- Yeah?

826
00:35:56.737 --> 00:35:58.947
Okay.
- Okay. good idea.

827
00:35:58.948 --> 00:36:00.866
- [sighs]

828
00:36:00.867 --> 00:36:02.951
Somebody found a baby?
- Yeah.

829
00:36:02.952 --> 00:36:05.370
Not the first time
it's happened.

830
00:36:05.371 --> 00:36:07.205
So. about those pills I took--

831
00:36:07.206 --> 00:36:10.250
- Oh. don't worry
about it. Doc.

832
00:36:10.251 --> 00:36:13.628
If the pills helped you. great.

833
00:36:13.629 --> 00:36:15.881
I never really liked
taking 'em.

834
00:36:15.882 --> 00:36:17.799
[both chuckle]

835
00:36:17.800 --> 00:36:19.384
- I appreciate that. Louie.

836
00:36:19.385 --> 00:36:21.386
That's not really
the point. but...

837
00:36:21.387 --> 00:36:23.805
I need to lift up
your shirt for a second.

838
00:36:23.806 --> 00:36:26.851
- [groans. sighs]

839
00:36:29.770 --> 00:36:32.147
- How long has your belly
been hard like that?

840
00:36:32.148 --> 00:36:33.607
- I don't know.

841
00:36:33.608 --> 00:36:35.734
I figured I could wait
another week.

842
00:36:35.735 --> 00:36:37.777
- You need. uh. some lab tests

843
00:36:37.778 --> 00:36:40.614
and a procedure to drain off
some of this fluid.

844
00:36:40.615 --> 00:36:42.616
- Yeah. I know the drill.

845
00:36:42.617 --> 00:36:44.993
I've been tapped
a few times before.

846
00:36:44.994 --> 00:36:48.205
- Three times
in the last six months.

847
00:36:48.206 --> 00:36:50.999
You need to give your liver
a break. Louie.

848
00:36:51.000 --> 00:36:52.418
- Yeah. I know.

849
00:36:57.006 --> 00:36:59.007
- I just heard somebody
dumped a baby

850
00:36:59.008 --> 00:37:00.425
in the waiting-room bathroom.

851
00:37:00.426 --> 00:37:03.637
How sad is that?
- Huh?

852
00:37:03.638 --> 00:37:06.765
- What's up with you today.
Mel... ancholia?

853
00:37:06.766 --> 00:37:09.184
- What makes you think
there's something up with me?

854
00:37:09.185 --> 00:37:10.977
- You're moping
around here all day

855
00:37:10.978 --> 00:37:13.438
like somebody gunned down
your favorite K-Pop band.

856
00:37:13.439 --> 00:37:15.440
- I don't really have
a favorite K-Pop band.

857
00:37:15.441 --> 00:37:17.275
It's not that I don't like
the genre.

858
00:37:17.276 --> 00:37:19.027
It's just kinda--
- Okay. forget K-Pop.

859
00:37:19.028 --> 00:37:20.654
What's going on with you?

860
00:37:20.655 --> 00:37:22.030
You usually ride in here

861
00:37:22.031 --> 00:37:23.823
on your unicorn
tossing wildflowers.

862
00:37:23.824 --> 00:37:26.534
- "Unicorn"?
- [sighs] Never mind.

863
00:37:26.535 --> 00:37:29.037
Is everything okay
with your sister?

864
00:37:29.038 --> 00:37:30.789
- Oh. yeah. she's great.

865
00:37:30.790 --> 00:37:32.832
It's just this...

866
00:37:32.833 --> 00:37:34.501
[stammers]

867
00:37:34.502 --> 00:37:36.670
- Spill. girl.

868
00:37:36.671 --> 00:37:38.296
- Um...

869
00:37:38.297 --> 00:37:41.675
well. a-a couple months ago.
I got named in a...

870
00:37:41.676 --> 00:37:43.843
[whispering]
Malpractice lawsuit.

871
00:37:43.844 --> 00:37:47.722
And so. um. today
is the--the deposition.

872
00:37:47.723 --> 00:37:49.432
- That's it?

873
00:37:49.433 --> 00:37:52.602
Every emergency-medicine doc
gets sued sooner or later.

874
00:37:52.603 --> 00:37:55.021
Seriously. don't sweat it.
You're still a resident.

875
00:37:55.022 --> 00:37:56.690
We're protected
by the hospital.

876
00:37:56.691 --> 00:38:00.527
You could cut somebody's head
off and get away with it.

877
00:38:00.528 --> 00:38:02.946
But. you know. like. don't.

878
00:38:02.947 --> 00:38:05.407
You don't want to become
known as the one

879
00:38:05.408 --> 00:38:07.993
who put Mel in mel-practice.

880
00:38:07.994 --> 00:38:10.829
- Hey. Santos. our little girl.
Kylie. has been

881
00:38:10.830 --> 00:38:14.082
in the West Penn Emergency
Department a couple times.

882
00:38:14.083 --> 00:38:16.710
- I'm not saying this
is necessarily the case here.

883
00:38:16.711 --> 00:38:19.504
but recent studies
have linked bullying behavior

884
00:38:19.505 --> 00:38:22.424
to different
personality disorders.

885
00:38:22.425 --> 00:38:25.093
On the other hand. though.
I-I am known to be a bit

886
00:38:25.094 --> 00:38:26.553
overly sensitive sometimes--

887
00:38:26.554 --> 00:38:27.762
- Mel.
- Yes?

888
00:38:27.763 --> 00:38:29.097
- You're talking
to yourself again.

889
00:38:29.098 --> 00:38:30.932
You need something?
- Uh. yeah. a good lawyer.

890
00:38:30.933 --> 00:38:32.726
[chuckles]
I don't know. I'm kidding.

891
00:38:32.727 --> 00:38:34.020
I'm--

892
00:38:35.938 --> 00:38:38.148
- Yo. Robinavitch. somebody
ditched a bundle of joy

893
00:38:38.149 --> 00:38:39.441
in chairs.

894
00:38:39.442 --> 00:38:40.900
- How old?
- Couple months maybe.

895
00:38:40.901 --> 00:38:42.319
Donahue's got her in Pedes.

896
00:38:42.320 --> 00:38:44.779
- No one saw who left her?
- Apparently not.

897
00:38:44.780 --> 00:38:46.531
- That's so sad.
- Tell me about it.

898
00:38:46.532 --> 00:38:48.074
Who throws away
a perfectly good baby?

899
00:38:48.075 --> 00:38:49.242
- [laughs]

900
00:38:49.243 --> 00:38:50.618
- Make a lane!

901
00:38:50.619 --> 00:38:53.121
- Ah. sweet baby Jesus.
Antoine!

902
00:38:53.122 --> 00:38:55.248
Right to the outdoor shower!
- I just drive 'em.

903
00:38:55.249 --> 00:38:56.708
I'm not
a wash and detail service.

904
00:38:56.709 --> 00:38:59.085
- Yeah. yeah.
God forbid you prove useful.

905
00:38:59.086 --> 00:39:00.670
Ah. good timing. Ms. Emma.

906
00:39:00.671 --> 00:39:03.381
Time for you and me to do
the Lord's work. This way.

907
00:39:03.382 --> 00:39:05.300
- Ooh. God. what is that?

908
00:39:05.301 --> 00:39:09.054
- Okay. big breath.
- [breathes deeply]

909
00:39:09.055 --> 00:39:13.017
- All right. lungs sound great.
Can you lean forward for me?

910
00:39:18.564 --> 00:39:22.317
Uh. did you hit your back
when you fell down the stairs?

911
00:39:22.318 --> 00:39:23.443
- No.

912
00:39:23.444 --> 00:39:25.320
- Okay. there's
a pretty good bruise here.

913
00:39:25.321 --> 00:39:27.198
- I got knocked down in soccer.

914
00:39:29.241 --> 00:39:32.077
- Oh. no. you broke your wrist
last year. too. huh?

915
00:39:32.078 --> 00:39:34.913
- Fell off my skateboard.
Got a purple cast.

916
00:39:34.914 --> 00:39:36.498
- Cool color.

917
00:39:36.499 --> 00:39:38.458
- And you were treated
at West Penn?

918
00:39:38.459 --> 00:39:40.919
Is that your closest hospital?

919
00:39:40.920 --> 00:39:42.670
- Uh. I guess
that would make sense.

920
00:39:42.671 --> 00:39:44.672
I've only been dating her dad
a few months.

921
00:39:44.673 --> 00:39:47.425
Uh. he lived in Garfield
before the divorce.

922
00:39:47.426 --> 00:39:49.928
- And. uh. what about these?
- Soccer.

923
00:39:49.929 --> 00:39:51.638
- Do you wear shin guards?

924
00:39:51.639 --> 00:39:53.306
- My dad ordered them.

925
00:39:53.307 --> 00:39:56.684
- Okay. What does your dad do
for work?

926
00:39:56.685 --> 00:39:59.562
- He draws buildings.
but he's not an architect.

927
00:39:59.563 --> 00:40:01.981
- He's a draftsman
for a firm in Newcastle.

928
00:40:01.982 --> 00:40:06.403
- Okay. Um. Kylie.
any chance you can pee?

929
00:40:06.404 --> 00:40:08.822
- Mm. maybe.
- Okay.

930
00:40:08.823 --> 00:40:10.865
Well. with the bruise
on your back.

931
00:40:10.866 --> 00:40:12.450
we need to check your urine.

932
00:40:12.451 --> 00:40:14.036
- Okay.
- Okay.

933
00:40:16.956 --> 00:40:19.332
- Did you eat anything
out of the ordinary recently?

934
00:40:19.333 --> 00:40:20.792
- No.

935
00:40:20.793 --> 00:40:23.211
Sorry. but we went
through this a bunch.

936
00:40:23.212 --> 00:40:24.879
Don't you people communicate?

937
00:40:24.880 --> 00:40:26.798
You're the third nurse
we've told her story to.

938
00:40:26.799 --> 00:40:28.133
- I'm a doctor.

939
00:40:28.134 --> 00:40:31.136
- Richard. would you go
to the cafeteria

940
00:40:31.137 --> 00:40:33.555
and get me
a large chamomile tea?

941
00:40:33.556 --> 00:40:35.723
What can we get you. my dear?

942
00:40:35.724 --> 00:40:38.060
- I'm fine. thank you.

943
00:40:40.020 --> 00:40:41.856
- Yeah. I'll be right back.

944
00:40:45.693 --> 00:40:48.111
- Please excuse my son.

945
00:40:48.112 --> 00:40:50.029
Ever since my husband died.

946
00:40:50.030 --> 00:40:52.449
he's been
a little overprotective.

947
00:40:52.450 --> 00:40:54.492
- I think it's sweet.

948
00:40:54.493 --> 00:40:57.371
You're very lucky to have him.
- I am.

949
00:40:58.956 --> 00:41:02.876
- Are you still taking your
loperamide and cholestyramine?

950
00:41:02.877 --> 00:41:05.670
- Um. mm. not so much.

951
00:41:05.671 --> 00:41:07.380
- No?

952
00:41:07.381 --> 00:41:09.799
That may be why you're
experiencing the abdominal pain

953
00:41:09.800 --> 00:41:11.426
and vomiting.

954
00:41:11.427 --> 00:41:13.678
When did you stop taking
your meds?

955
00:41:13.679 --> 00:41:15.848
- Last winter or so.

956
00:41:17.850 --> 00:41:21.519
My neighbor Helen and I bingo
in Wintersville.

957
00:41:21.520 --> 00:41:24.189
There's a dispensary next door.

958
00:41:24.190 --> 00:41:26.232
And we got some marijuana.

959
00:41:26.233 --> 00:41:30.528
And I swear
it cleared everything up.

960
00:41:30.529 --> 00:41:34.073
A few cookies
every few hours...

961
00:41:34.074 --> 00:41:36.743
and no more pain.

962
00:41:36.744 --> 00:41:39.287
- "A few cookies"?

963
00:41:39.288 --> 00:41:41.414
How many are you eating
in a day?

964
00:41:41.415 --> 00:41:43.500
- Oh. uh...

965
00:41:43.501 --> 00:41:46.169
I don't know.

966
00:41:46.170 --> 00:41:51.090
Probably a dozen or so.
but they're not very big.

967
00:41:51.091 --> 00:41:53.092
- There have been some studies

968
00:41:53.093 --> 00:41:55.303
that show
an added dementia risk

969
00:41:55.304 --> 00:41:58.307
with marijuana use
in older adults.

970
00:41:59.683 --> 00:42:02.393
- Well. that sucks
for old people.

971
00:42:02.394 --> 00:42:03.728
[urine trickling]

972
00:42:03.729 --> 00:42:05.688
- Kylie.
there are some questions

973
00:42:05.689 --> 00:42:09.734
that we ask every kid
who comes in with an injury.

974
00:42:09.735 --> 00:42:11.277
- Like what?

975
00:42:11.278 --> 00:42:14.739
- Like. sometimes the people
that you live with

976
00:42:14.740 --> 00:42:19.744
can get so mad that
they hit you or hurt you.

977
00:42:19.745 --> 00:42:21.955
maybe without even meaning to.

978
00:42:21.956 --> 00:42:23.414
Does that ever happen?

979
00:42:23.415 --> 00:42:25.917
- No. not to me.

980
00:42:25.918 --> 00:42:28.127
- Or sometimes kids
can get punished

981
00:42:28.128 --> 00:42:29.754
for doing something wrong

982
00:42:29.755 --> 00:42:33.299
with maybe a spanking
or a belt.

983
00:42:33.300 --> 00:42:35.969
- I get time-outs.

984
00:42:35.970 --> 00:42:38.096
- How about at school. Kylie?

985
00:42:38.097 --> 00:42:41.599
You know. is anybody being.
you know. mean or bullying you?

986
00:42:41.600 --> 00:42:44.186
- No. I have lots of friends.

987
00:42:47.314 --> 00:42:48.314
- [clears throat]

988
00:42:48.315 --> 00:42:50.901
[toilet flushing]

989
00:42:53.737 --> 00:42:56.282
[water running]

990
00:43:04.999 --> 00:43:07.166
- Yo. Whitaker.

991
00:43:07.167 --> 00:43:10.003
- Dr. Langdon.

992
00:43:10.004 --> 00:43:13.798
- You. uh. meet Louie here?
- Uh. yeah. yeah. many times.

993
00:43:13.799 --> 00:43:16.175
Good morning. Mr. Cloverfield.
- What's up. Doc?

994
00:43:16.176 --> 00:43:18.386
- Where's your new resident
badge buddy. buddy?

995
00:43:18.387 --> 00:43:22.724
- Oh. uh. yeah. they--they
didn't give me a new one yet.

996
00:43:22.725 --> 00:43:24.058
- Bummer.

997
00:43:24.059 --> 00:43:25.643
You and. uh.
your ducklings got time

998
00:43:25.644 --> 00:43:27.312
to tap a six-pack
off our friend here?

999
00:43:27.313 --> 00:43:29.856
Louie needs a paracentesis.
- Yeah. sure.

1000
00:43:29.857 --> 00:43:31.816
It's good to see you
again. Louie--

1001
00:43:31.817 --> 00:43:33.568
not in this condition.
of course.

1002
00:43:33.569 --> 00:43:34.652
How you feeling?

1003
00:43:34.653 --> 00:43:37.989
- Feeling like I need
a drink pretty soon.

1004
00:43:37.990 --> 00:43:39.824
- Okay. well.
first things first--

1005
00:43:39.825 --> 00:43:42.076
we are going to make you
more comfortable

1006
00:43:42.077 --> 00:43:43.703
by draining some fluid.

1007
00:43:43.704 --> 00:43:45.413
- You're gonna take off
a big volume.

1008
00:43:45.414 --> 00:43:48.541
so start with 60 grams
of 25% albumin IV.

1009
00:43:48.542 --> 00:43:51.127
You tapped him before?
- No.

1010
00:43:51.128 --> 00:43:53.630
- That's okay. Doc.
I'll talk him through it.

1011
00:43:53.631 --> 00:43:55.382
- [chuckles]
Okay.

1012
00:43:57.009 --> 00:44:00.429
- Sats 99 on room air.
normal BP. normal pulse.

1013
00:44:03.223 --> 00:44:04.891
- Oh. well hydrated.

1014
00:44:04.892 --> 00:44:06.643
- No obvious source
of infection.

1015
00:44:06.644 --> 00:44:09.646
Could be a benign virus.
but can't assume that.

1016
00:44:09.647 --> 00:44:12.273
- Is this the abandoned baby?
- Mm-hmm.

1017
00:44:12.274 --> 00:44:14.651
- How old?
- How old do you think she is?

1018
00:44:14.652 --> 00:44:18.071
- Month. month and a half?
- It's tricky.

1019
00:44:18.072 --> 00:44:21.449
Under 28 days is a Safe Haven
drop-off. no questions asked.

1020
00:44:21.450 --> 00:44:24.911
But over 28 days is a crime.
child abandonment.

1021
00:44:24.912 --> 00:44:27.080
- How should we assess?

1022
00:44:27.081 --> 00:44:30.208
- Under 28 days gets everything.
including an LP.

1023
00:44:30.209 --> 00:44:32.543
But over 28 days.

1024
00:44:32.544 --> 00:44:34.712
you can follow PECARN
or Step-by-step

1025
00:44:34.713 --> 00:44:37.423
to determine risk of invasive
bacterial infection.

1026
00:44:37.424 --> 00:44:38.925
- This baby looks great.

1027
00:44:38.926 --> 00:44:40.885
- But we know nothing
about the birth history.

1028
00:44:40.886 --> 00:44:44.722
Did Mom have group B strep.
active HSV lesions?

1029
00:44:44.723 --> 00:44:48.768
- We should assume the worst.
Put in your orders. Dr. Mohan.

1030
00:44:48.769 --> 00:44:50.812
- CBC...
[sighs]

1031
00:44:50.813 --> 00:44:53.314
Blood culture. chem panel.

1032
00:44:53.315 --> 00:44:56.192
chest X-ray. UA and culture.

1033
00:44:56.193 --> 00:44:58.403
respiratory virus panel.

1034
00:44:58.404 --> 00:45:02.699
Check inflammatory markers--
procalcitonin and CRP--

1035
00:45:02.700 --> 00:45:04.784
then take it from there.

1036
00:45:04.785 --> 00:45:06.994
- That sounds like a plan.

1037
00:45:06.995 --> 00:45:09.163
- Dr. Robby.
Santos needs you in North 1.

1038
00:45:09.164 --> 00:45:10.707
- Okay. I'll be right there.

1039
00:45:10.708 --> 00:45:13.168
If you'll excuse me.
if you'll excuse me.

1040
00:45:15.504 --> 00:45:19.757
- Mind if I join with?
- Uh. no. I got this.

1041
00:45:19.758 --> 00:45:21.509
- It will help me
get a better sense

1042
00:45:21.510 --> 00:45:23.761
of how you like to do things
by seeing you in action

1043
00:45:23.762 --> 00:45:25.263
with the residents.

1044
00:45:25.264 --> 00:45:26.974
- Be my guest.

1045
00:45:29.685 --> 00:45:31.895
- I will be right back.

1046
00:45:36.984 --> 00:45:39.777
Um. nine-year-old
Kylie Connors--

1047
00:45:39.778 --> 00:45:41.821
took a tumble running up
the stairs this morning.

1048
00:45:41.822 --> 00:45:43.614
Chin lac and fractured tooth.

1049
00:45:43.615 --> 00:45:45.825
Brought in by her dad's
girlfriend. Gina.

1050
00:45:45.826 --> 00:45:48.953
Supposedly. the dad had
to leave early for work.

1051
00:45:48.954 --> 00:45:51.748
Kylie has a lot of bruising
on her body--

1052
00:45:51.749 --> 00:45:53.332
some old. some new.

1053
00:45:53.333 --> 00:45:56.919
- Are you concerned
about non-accidental trauma?

1054
00:45:56.920 --> 00:45:58.546
- Or worse.

1055
00:45:58.547 --> 00:46:01.007
Her urine sample shows
gross hematuria.

1056
00:46:01.008 --> 00:46:04.218
which could be renal injury.
or vaginal bleeding from trauma

1057
00:46:04.219 --> 00:46:06.471
could have contaminated
the specimen.

1058
00:46:06.472 --> 00:46:09.390
- Lots to consider.
What's your plan?

1059
00:46:09.391 --> 00:46:12.059
- Labs. ultrasound.
social-work consult.

1060
00:46:12.060 --> 00:46:14.103
then decide
if this is reportable.

1061
00:46:14.104 --> 00:46:15.522
- Mm-hmm.

1062
00:46:18.734 --> 00:46:20.568
- Let me know
if you can feel this.

1063
00:46:20.569 --> 00:46:22.403
- No.
Am I supposed to?

1064
00:46:22.404 --> 00:46:23.614
- No.

1065
00:46:27.826 --> 00:46:29.994
- Your hair's
such a pretty color.

1066
00:46:29.995 --> 00:46:31.204
- Thank you.

1067
00:46:31.205 --> 00:46:33.706
- Reminds me of my mom.

1068
00:46:33.707 --> 00:46:37.001
She died when I was nine.
- Oh. I'm sorry about that.

1069
00:46:37.002 --> 00:46:39.587
- She wore glasses
like you. too.

1070
00:46:39.588 --> 00:46:41.589
Weird.

1071
00:46:41.590 --> 00:46:45.009
What do you like to do
when you're not working?

1072
00:46:45.010 --> 00:46:47.428
- Um. spend some time
with my sister.

1073
00:46:47.429 --> 00:46:49.222
read.

1074
00:46:49.223 --> 00:46:50.848
- Do you drink coffee?

1075
00:46:50.849 --> 00:46:54.477
- Uh. no. I avoid caffeine.

1076
00:46:54.478 --> 00:46:55.603
- Me too.

1077
00:46:55.604 --> 00:46:57.271
Um...

1078
00:46:57.272 --> 00:46:59.274
what about boba?

1079
00:47:00.818 --> 00:47:04.321
- I love boba.
[chuckles]

1080
00:47:06.949 --> 00:47:08.950
- I'd offer you some gum.
but it's laced with nicotine.

1081
00:47:08.951 --> 00:47:10.827
Trying to quit smoking.

1082
00:47:10.828 --> 00:47:13.412
- [sighs]
That's good.

1083
00:47:13.413 --> 00:47:15.164
- Verdict's still out.

1084
00:47:15.165 --> 00:47:17.542
Get in all those nooks
and crannies. Mr. Digby.

1085
00:47:17.543 --> 00:47:19.418
Your skin will thank you.

1086
00:47:19.419 --> 00:47:21.337
We all will.

1087
00:47:21.338 --> 00:47:25.383
- Oh. I could stay
in here all day.

1088
00:47:25.384 --> 00:47:27.635
- It's a miracle what little
soap. water. and human decency

1089
00:47:27.636 --> 00:47:29.637
can do sometimes.

1090
00:47:29.638 --> 00:47:31.055
Don't forget the ears. pal.

1091
00:47:31.056 --> 00:47:33.057
Don't want anything
growing in there either.

1092
00:47:33.058 --> 00:47:34.642
- Okay. Okay.

1093
00:47:34.643 --> 00:47:36.561
- What's your story. Emma?

1094
00:47:36.562 --> 00:47:39.438
What'd your parents do?
Got siblings? Boyfriend?

1095
00:47:39.439 --> 00:47:42.400
Ever kill a man in a bar fight?

1096
00:47:42.401 --> 00:47:43.694
- Uh...

1097
00:47:45.571 --> 00:47:48.615
[indistinct chatter]
- [sighs]

1098
00:47:53.120 --> 00:47:55.454
So. Mr. Williams.

1099
00:47:55.455 --> 00:47:57.874
sometimes a fracture
of the scaphoid bone

1100
00:47:57.875 --> 00:47:59.750
doesn't show up on day one.

1101
00:47:59.751 --> 00:48:03.462
So my advice to be safe is
wear a splint for two weeks

1102
00:48:03.463 --> 00:48:05.673
and then come back
for a repeat X-ray.

1103
00:48:05.674 --> 00:48:07.466
and we'll see
if it's really there.

1104
00:48:07.467 --> 00:48:09.760
- [sighs]

1105
00:48:09.761 --> 00:48:12.388
My knee hurts.

1106
00:48:12.389 --> 00:48:15.725
- Oh. did you hurt your knee?

1107
00:48:15.726 --> 00:48:17.477
- I must have.

1108
00:48:24.026 --> 00:48:26.110
What is this?

1109
00:48:26.111 --> 00:48:29.030
- That's. um. for your wrist.

1110
00:48:29.031 --> 00:48:31.949
- And I need this?

1111
00:48:31.950 --> 00:48:34.702
- Well. um. if it's a. uh--

1112
00:48:34.703 --> 00:48:36.787
John. can you?

1113
00:48:36.788 --> 00:48:39.332
If it's a fracture
and we don't immobilize.

1114
00:48:39.333 --> 00:48:41.543
the bone might not heal
properly.

1115
00:48:43.503 --> 00:48:47.340
- [sighs]
How long is this gonna take?

1116
00:48:47.341 --> 00:48:49.760
- Just a few minutes
to fit you.

1117
00:48:52.638 --> 00:48:55.140
- Is this place new?

1118
00:48:57.851 --> 00:49:01.855
- Mr. Williams.
do you know what day it is?

1119
00:49:05.400 --> 00:49:07.944
- It's Taco Tuesday.

1120
00:49:07.945 --> 00:49:10.197
- Do you know where you are?

1121
00:49:11.698 --> 00:49:14.951
- Yeah. I'm in the slowest
medical clinic in the West.

1122
00:49:14.952 --> 00:49:17.411
- Do you know what year it is?

1123
00:49:17.412 --> 00:49:19.538
- How about you just
fix my wrist

1124
00:49:19.539 --> 00:49:23.751
and you stop
with all the questions?

1125
00:49:23.752 --> 00:49:26.838
I am not here to be profiled.

1126
00:49:31.009 --> 00:49:33.928
- Yeah. of course.

1127
00:49:33.929 --> 00:49:36.056
I'll be back. okay?

1128
00:49:39.434 --> 00:49:42.229
[inaudible speech]

1129
00:49:46.775 --> 00:49:49.527
- All right. Mr. Digby.
looking better already.

1130
00:49:49.528 --> 00:49:51.445
Certainly smell
a little better.

1131
00:49:51.446 --> 00:49:52.947
- Do you have any conditioner?

1132
00:49:52.948 --> 00:49:55.074
- Let's get you dried off
and back inside.

1133
00:49:55.075 --> 00:49:56.742
Get him gowned up
and put him in South 21.

1134
00:49:56.743 --> 00:49:57.910
across from the old nun.

1135
00:49:57.911 --> 00:50:01.205
Maybe some of her divine grace
will wear off on him.

1136
00:50:01.206 --> 00:50:02.540
Who do we have here?

1137
00:50:02.541 --> 00:50:05.459
- Evelyn Bostick. 81.
with Alzheimer's.

1138
00:50:05.460 --> 00:50:07.712
We brought her husband in
about 30 minutes ago.

1139
00:50:07.713 --> 00:50:09.338
She was supposed
to get a ride in.

1140
00:50:09.339 --> 00:50:11.007
but they found her
wandering in traffic.

1141
00:50:11.008 --> 00:50:13.050
- Where are we?
- You're at the hospital. dear.

1142
00:50:13.051 --> 00:50:14.427
- I'm not sick.

1143
00:50:14.428 --> 00:50:16.429
- We brought you
to see your husband.

1144
00:50:16.430 --> 00:50:18.431
- Oh. no.
Is Ethan okay?

1145
00:50:18.432 --> 00:50:21.017
- I'll be in to chat with you.
Mrs. Bostick.

1146
00:50:21.018 --> 00:50:23.561
He died.

1147
00:50:23.562 --> 00:50:25.438
What you got. Amboy?

1148
00:50:25.439 --> 00:50:28.649
- Allen Billings--had a pallet
fall onto his outstretched arm.

1149
00:50:28.650 --> 00:50:31.068
Looks like an open dislocation.
- Yeah. that's got to hurt.

1150
00:50:31.069 --> 00:50:32.778
Don't worry. sir.
We got you.

1151
00:50:32.779 --> 00:50:35.907
- [breathing heavily]

1152
00:50:38.827 --> 00:50:42.079
- How's she doing?
- Seems happy enough.

1153
00:50:42.080 --> 00:50:44.081
- Yeah. Hi.
- Hi.

1154
00:50:44.082 --> 00:50:46.834
Just got a quick
point-of-care CBC.

1155
00:50:46.835 --> 00:50:48.670
- [chuckles]

1156
00:50:53.258 --> 00:50:55.260
Is there a problem?

1157
00:50:58.764 --> 00:51:00.598
Did I miss something?

1158
00:51:00.599 --> 00:51:03.602
Dr. Al? Dr. Al?

